Iâ€™ve come to a similar conclusion:

Suffering and pain are only natural experiences in life. After tragedy or trauma we still have energy left. Either it can be used for destruction or creation. 

Natural forces of destruction in the Universe are far more powerful than any of humanity. So we must choose creation of beauty. 

Poetic that the detail of beauty we can create is far greater than anything the Universe can create. It is, what makes us special as a species. 
We must create. 
I must create.

Don't think enough people acknowledge how attention spans have truly altered filmmaking: 

The Wire's Bible (from the turn of the millennium) took 79 pages (http://kottke.org.s3.amazonaws.com/the-wire/The_Wire_-_Bible.pdf) to be picked up by HBO 

True Detective's Bible (from the teens) only took 10 pages (https://thescriptlab.com/wp-content/uploads/scripts/TrueDetective_Bible.pdf) to be picked up by HBO 

True Decective also does some legwork for execs around how to syndicate and run the show structure. Imagine how even more focused and succinct the bibles of today have to be...

cast.text:
This is a big deal. Neon winning two Best Pictures off the Cannes-to-Oscars vector isn't just a statistical anomalyâ€”it's a signal flare in the smog-choked wreckage of commercial cinema. The Hollywood IP-industrial complex is a zombie protocol, endlessly self-replicating, stripping its own archives for collagen. Meanwhile, China's film industry is an airlocked simulation, pre-sanitized for ideological hygiene.

Neon's success is a glitch in the corporate entertainment stack, an unexpected breach where a different stack syncs across circuits. It means the old arthouse-to-mainstream feedback loop, presumed dead, still has some cycles left as combustion accelerant.

European and South Asian cinema with American money as completion bonds aren't just a holdout; they're the beachhead of what comes next. A speculative tech stack producing artifacts that remind us the future isn't lockedâ€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹â€‹

cast.text:
In our on going saga of Netflix destroys all... Netflix is now worth more than Disney, Comcast, Warner Bros. Discovery and Paramount combined (by a margin of a whole Warner Bros + Paramount too). 

To make matters worse for everyone else, Netflix is just getting their ad offering underway, while everyone else is pretty maxed out. The old guard are all currently in some stage of trying to chop off their linear tv offerings too. This'll cut down on cost, but at the expense of a big portion of their own ad offerings. 

Netflix's moat is only likely to widen as their $18B spend for 2025 and distribution to some 300M subscribes will continue to make them the first stop to shop movies/tv. 

And then there are live events, which Netflix is just dipping their toes into.. Old guard will be lucky to survive without merging with each other. 

But what they really need is an offering that Netflix can't match like a reinvention of the filmmaking process for all... 
Old guard. /filmatree will soon help reverse the tide

cast.text:
One plausible future reality

1. 80% of posts don't earn anything
2. 19% of posts earn <$100
3. 1% of posts earn >$100

Don't focus on the exact percentages, napkin math, adjust for spam, etc. 

But the apply the same power laws that already exist internet, but possibly, you get better monetization for the middle cohort. And then the power law winners capture more of the upside instead of the platforms.

I loved Jamie XXâ€™s In Colour when it came out 10 years ago. 

When he dropped In Waves a few months ago I wasnâ€™t into it. Chopped it up to too much time away. BUT giving it a second chance with fresh ears and can say itâ€™s grown on me. 

It feels like a proper reflection of how quickly we live our lives now. Less colorful, poppy sounds for more more dnb rhythms and harder breaks.

Easy enough to work to, but not the right music to live too. Opportunity to the up & coming artists that want to bring color and vibrancy back to the forefront.

cast.text:
In our on going saga of Netflix destroys all... Netflix is now worth more than Disney, Comcast, Warner Bros. Discovery and Paramount combined (by a margin of a whole Warner Bros + Paramount too). 

To make matters worse for everyone else, Netflix is just getting their ad offering underway, while everyone else is pretty maxed out. The old guard are all currently in some stage of trying to chop off their linear tv offerings too. This'll cut down on cost, but at the expense of a big portion of their own ad offerings. 

Netflix's moat is only likely to widen as their $18B spend for 2025 and distribution to some 300M subscribes will continue to make them the first stop to shop movies/tv. 

And then there are live events, which Netflix is just dipping their toes into.. Old guard will be lucky to survive without merging with each other. 

But what they really need is an offering that Netflix can't match like a reinvention of the filmmaking process for all... 
Old guard. /filmatree will soon help reverse the tide
